</div>
				
				<div>
					
					
				</div>
				<div>   </div>
			</div>					
		
	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>WoW would probably be perfect for y'all then =)<br />
<br />
1. Downtime is cut way back first of all. You can acquire food/drink which regens your hp/mana very fast. From having 5% hp/mana, you could be back at 100% in 10-15 seconds =) Food and drink drops off mobs, can be created with tradeskills and Mages can even summon them for free.<br />
<br />
2. Soloing is viable for pretty much every class (though some are, of course, better than others at it). Granted, this is for grinding. You'll need a group for the harder quests.<br />
<br />
Duoing is even better, you can do fantastically as a couple (my wife and I have a mage/priest combo which works amazingly well). You also don't HAVE to do a healer/tank or two kiting classes to make it work, just pick what you want to play and it'll most likely be just fine.<br />
<br />
3. If your time gets limited, then WoW's rest system will be a nice treat for y'all. Basically, when you're logged off you accumulate 'rested' experience such that you will gain 200% exp off a mob until you reach that point.<br />
<br />
For example: When you normally kill a turtle, you get 100 exp. While you're in the rested state, you will get 200 exp for the kill. Effectively, this means that in an hour's gametime, you do two hours worth of killing (if it's all rested exp).<br />
<br />
Rested experience grows at a rate of about 1 bubble (there are 20 bubs in an exp bar) per eight hours. This is in an Inn by the way. You gain rested experience 4x faster in an Inn than if you log off in the wilderness. Oh and you also get a Hearthstone in the beginning of the game which gives you a free teleport to the Inn you're bound at (it has a 60 minute cooldown timer).<br />
<br />
Never seen it myself, but I've heard you can get 30 bars of rested exp max. So that's a level and a half where each mob gives a boatload of exp =) <br />
<br />
And there are some quests with a timer in WoW, but they are few and far between.<br />
<br />
<br />
4. Both EQ2 and WoW have a good amount of quests, but WoW's system is definately superior. There's a lot of lore in them, and the rewards are very awesome. Even if it's just money, you'll usually get a nice amount of experience as well.<br />
<br />
I've went out before and completed about 7 quests then, came back to town after levelling. When I did the quest finishes, I gained over half a level of experience.<br />
<br />
Also, EQ2 quest givers often have you running a long, long ways to get to where the mobs are. Gets kinda old when you start in one place, run 15-20 mins to kill a few mobs (or just talk to someone), then run back. So actual questing time = 5 or 10 minutes while travel time = 40. Bleh hehe<br />
<br />
<br />
However, I only played EQ2 in beta so I don't have much experience with mid-late game.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
