		<div>You must remember that many of the WoW fans here are also ferverent Sony haters, therefore they tend to be biased against Everquest 2. And indeed you can see that in many posts in this thread and others. Any game is going to take time to play, so when someone raves about how wonderful X is to Y, you have to wonder just how much time they actually spent playing Y. <br />
<br />
For instance, someone said WoW gives you experience for exploring. Well, Everquest 2 does as well. Also, stating that WoW has more quests than Everquest 2 is just ludicrous. Anyone who really has played either game would know that there are so many quests in both games it would be very difficult for one person to have quantified them, especially so soon after the games' releases. One may argue the flavor of the world and its quests, but that is a matter of opinion. Many say the WoW quests are funny and satirical, which is fine if you like that. I prefer more of straight fantasy setting, which is why I also did not like WoW's cartoon graphics. I haven't played WoW, but I have seen screenshots and videos, and it reminds me of a large version of Warcarft III, another game I didn't like. <br />
<br />
One of the flaws of Everquest 2, at least a flaw that made me quit playing EQ2, was the Heroic Opportunities in groups. Having made those, you become a slave to the group. You cannot cast or use any abilities without ruining the Heroic Opportunities. It is also made worse by the fact when I was playing, the game would erronously report who kept ruining Heroic Opportunies, confusing everyone and making it difficult to figure out which person needed a talking to. For a major feature to still have errors like that was a big disappointment for me. (Plus I also made a gnome, and had to get so close to the monster that my whole screen was filled up by a buttcheek before I could get in range to melee and therefore couldnt see a damn thing that was going on.) I also think it was a mistake to require people to complete these stupid &quot;class&quot; quests in order to progress, when most of them are just to make a simple choice (do I want to be a bard or a rogue?). They say the quests help you figure out which class you want to play, but quite honestly it does not, it just makes you run through several zones. However, that only occurs 3 times in your life in Everquest, so it is not too bad. Soloing in Everquest 2 is quite viable, although there is a big emphasis on group work. Playing with 2 characters is quite doable, I think. I found Everquest 2 to be quite stable and very good performance considering its features and the age of my computer, although zone loading times were slow.</div>
