		<!-- message -->
		<div>While I agree with the above poster about the Sony haters, I will disagree about EQ2. I don't hate Sony, or even EQ (still have my account open, but it will probably be closing sooner than later) but EQ2 is one my least favorite games. Given I have only played in beta, and at that not even the latter stages so some of this info may be out of date and I would enjoy any corrections. <br />
<br />
For starters, there are really only 4 classes. Sure you have to chose a sepereate path a few times, but since every class has to fill every role in it's archetype to some extent class individuality is completely gone. I hear they tried to fix this the last week of beta, but I have little faith that they could get it to work so quickly. While a limited class selection is nice in some ways, I would prefer if they just did not try to make it seem like there are far more classes than there are.<br />
<br />
Tradeskills are way better in WoW imo as well. This is mainly because EQ and EQ2 never really appealed to me for tradeskills. EQ2 loses my with the being able to die doing a tradeskill combine. I never really got much into them though because of that possibility. WoW's tradeskills are not only easy and rewarding, they are super addictive. I have more than once been finding myself way short on cash just to get a few more recipes. The ingredients are also fairly common, with  few exceptions. Most of the materials you will find in level appropriate areas and some off of level appropriate mobs. Occasionally a recipe may call for a rare component, but it is usually well worth it.<br />
<br />
Now the biggest thing problem I have with EQ2 is the stupidly easy pulling system. Mobs will either single, or come in a group, as determined by the mob and not how you pull them. No longer can you analyze agro ranges, assisst ranges, and general walking paths of a few mobs in an attempt to get no more than you can handle on a pull, no. Now you simply click the mob and the game shows you how your pull will turn out, and if a creature is going to assisst it will regardless of your efforts. I hate that.<br />
<br />
Also looking at screenshots of WoW really don't give you a good idea of how immersive the game really is. The world is very much alive and it shows with the way everything moves and works together.</div>
