	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>Figure I will put my 2 copper in since I have played both EQ2 and WoW.<br />
<br />
My situation is similar to yours where the wife and I have kids, so our time online is limited in the evenings. Sort of puts a damper on raiding in EQ when we're CST, and most guilds are EST from our experiance (at least, that's when they raid) and start waaaaaaay too early (kids aren't in bed yet). <br />
<br />
With that being said...<br />
<br />
WoW has pleased us very, very much because of the time we have available (few hours a night) to play anymore. We can login for 30 minutes or so and work on quests, xp, whatever and get gratification at the end of the night that we actually accomplished something. With having a family, your time is your time and you want it to start immediately when you're available... most raids in EQ just never happen like that.<br />
<br />
On duo-classes, I think you can pretty much be any class/race combo for each of you and be happy (alliance/alliance, or horde/horde) with it. If you're anything like me, you will both want to play together to share the experiance of the game. We have tried various combos and all have worked well together (warlock/priest, hunter/hunter, warrior/cleric, rogue/druid, mage/mage) in WoW. Blizzard did something right by allowing basically any class to solo their way up for the casual player like me or my wife.<br />
<br />
Now, on to EQ2. We tried this for a few weeks as well, and there were a few things that we didn't like as a couple...<br />
<br />
1) We had to pick classes that complimented each other - this simply was not the case in WoW<br />
<br />
2) Resource requirements - the requirements are hefty... very hefty... if your pc can handle them, great, if not... may want to look elsewhere...<br />
<br />
3) Quest system - we preferred the quest system in WoW as we found it was 100 times easier to understand and use, this is our preferance though, and your mileage may vary<br />
<br />
EQ2 was a good game, it just wasn't for us, we gave it a nice healthy shot at trying to become our 'game' of choice, just didn't happen. Before people start doing the graphics comparison of the games, let me say this....<br />
<br />
Regardless of graphics, a game is meant to be fun. A game can have the best graphics in the world, but play like crap (tons of examples of this out there), and then the opposite end of the spectrum is true that a game can look like crap, but be fun as ever to play. That's probably the reason we still play EQ, we have fun playing, which is the most important part.<br />
<br />
Both of us coming from the background of playing MUDs (text-based eq anyone? <img src="images/smilies/biggrin.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Big Grin" class="inlineimg" />) we don't have to have the flashy graphics to find something fun, and prefer to play as a couple.<br />
<br />
As always, this is just my opinion of the games, so take it for what you will.</div>
