		<!-- message -->
		<div>This is coming from someone who hasn't played WoW and likes EQ2, so it will be somewhat biased in that sense...<br />
<br />
1. Down time: With good food and water downtime is very limited, I don't think I have ever had to wait longer than a minute or two.  This is useally because I duo with a Paladin so we generally use up all our power in the fight.  If we didn't cheap out and bought the really good food our downtime would be even less.  We just don't need to have 100% uptime so it's not a big deal to us.<br />
<br />
2. Solo/ duoability: You can solo and duo up to level 30 at least.  I've been doing it and there is no lack of solo content in EQ2.  They are even going to be adding more, I'm guessing for the higher levels. <br />
<br />
3. Time sink: Considering it's a MMORPG there are going to be timesinks.  Although they mostly seem to be running around travelling, which could be cut down if I can ever afford a horse.  I have only had to camp one spot once for an armor quest and that was because I didn't have the patience to check out the other spots for a non-common (wasn't really rare) spawn.<br />
<br />
4. Quests: These are 10000x better in EQ2 than they were in EQ1.  My wizard is wearing a full suit of quested armor because he hasn't found anything better yet.  The quested gear is quite nice, if you happen to know about the quests.  The armor quests for both Paladin and Wizard could be duo'd with a Wizard / Paladin with the execption of one fight each where we needed a healer.<br />
<br />
The downside to EQ2 is the system requirements.  It is hefty.  They do have a memory leak which makes your FPS plummet after a while though not everyone experiences it.  Apparently they have made good strides on fixing it with the next major update.<br />
<br />
I'm not saying EQ2 is a better solo/duo game than WoW because I just don't know.  I just disagree a lot with Flintnilf in his comments about, for the reasons stated above:<br />
